TY  - JOUR
AU  - Ball, Sheryl
AU  - Eckel, Catherine
AU  - Grossman, Philip J.
AU  - Zame, William
T1  - Status in Markets*
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/02/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355301556374
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 116
IS  - 1
SP  - 161
EP  - 188
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This project tests for the effect of social status in a laboratory experimental market. We consider a special “box design” market in which a vertical overlap in supply and demand ensure that there are multiple equilibrium prices. We manipulate the relative social status of our subjects by awarding high status to a subset of the group based on one of two procedures. In the first, a subject's score on a trivia quiz determines his or her status; in another, subjects are assigned randomly to a higher-status or lower-status group. In both treatments we find that average prices are higher in markets where higher-status sellers face lowerstatus buyers, and lower when buyers have higher status than sellers. Across all sessions, the higher-status side of the market captures a greater share of the surplus, earning significantly more than their lower-status counterparts.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355301556374
ER  - 



