TY  - JOUR
AU  - Andreoni, James
AU  - Vesterlund, Lise
T1  - Which is the Fair Sex? Gender Differences in Altruism*
PY  - 2001
Y1  - 2001/02/01
DO  - 10.1162/003355301556419
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 116
IS  - 1
SP  - 293
EP  - 312
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We study gender differences in altruism by examining a modified dictator game with varying incomes and prices. Our results indicate that the question “which is the fair sex?” has a complicated answer—when altruism is expensive, women are kinder, but when it is cheap, men are more altruistic. That is, we find that the male and female “demand curves for altruism” cross, and that men are more responsive to price changes. Furthermore, men are more likely to be either perfectly selfish or perfectly selfless, whereas women tend to be “equalitarians” who prefer to share evenly.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1162/003355301556419
ER  - 



